00:12:18.530 --> 00:12:22.750
"Somerville was so impressed by
Ada's sharp reasoning skills,

00:12:22.750 --> 00:12:25.340
she invited Ada and
her mother to a party.

00:12:25.340 --> 00:12:30.180
Not just a party for dancing and
dining, but for sharing ideas.

00:12:30.180 --> 00:12:32.740
The guests were scientists
like Michael Faraday, who

00:12:32.740 --> 00:12:35.970
studied electromagnetism,
and Charles Wheatstone

00:12:35.970 --> 00:12:39.810
who invented a device to display
three-dimensional images.

00:12:39.810 --> 00:12:42.230
But for Ada, the one
who mattered most

00:12:42.230 --> 00:12:43.990
was Charles Babbage.

00:12:43.990 --> 00:12:46.400
He was a famous
mathematician and inventor,

00:12:46.400 --> 00:12:48.820
just like Ada wanted to be.

00:12:48.820 --> 00:12:51.950
Though she was only
17 and Babbage 41,

00:12:51.950 --> 00:12:55.150
Ada spoke about math with a
precision and understanding

00:12:55.150 --> 00:12:58.950
that impressed him, so much
so that Babbage invited

00:12:58.950 --> 00:13:02.820
her to visit his laboratory."

00:13:02.820 --> 00:13:06.170
Funny thing about this spread
has nothing to do with my book,

00:13:06.170 --> 00:13:09.520
but has to do with
Google Boston.

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:12.250
I was in Google
Boston two weeks ago

00:13:12.250 --> 00:13:15.370
giving Take Your Child
to Work Day events.

00:13:15.370 --> 00:13:19.480
And I was in the
Charles Babbage room.

00:13:19.480 --> 00:13:23.592
They also have an Ada Lovelace
room and a Grace Hopper room.

00:13:23.592 --> 00:13:25.300
And I'm writing a book
about Grace Hopper

00:13:25.300 --> 00:13:27.340
that comes out next year.

00:13:27.340 --> 00:13:28.830
But I was in the Babbage room.

00:13:31.420 --> 00:13:34.170
"Ada brought her journals to
show him her own experiments

00:13:34.170 --> 00:13:35.450
and inventions.

00:13:35.450 --> 00:13:37.750
Their tea grew cold as they
talked about their love

00:13:37.750 --> 00:13:40.140
of machines and mathematics.

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:42.690
Babbage didn't see her
as simply a young girl.

00:13:42.690 --> 00:13:45.460
He treated her like the fellow
mathematician and inventor

00:13:45.460 --> 00:13:47.380
she already was.

00:13:47.380 --> 00:13:50.590
Before, numbers had
been Ada's only friends.

00:13:50.590 --> 00:13:54.210
Now Babbage was a
friend as well."

00:13:54.210 --> 00:13:54.710
OK.

00:13:58.190 --> 00:14:03.820
Ada's looking at a mechanical
doll that Babbage had.

00:14:03.820 --> 00:14:05.900
But look at her
magnifying glass.

00:14:05.900 --> 00:14:07.880
What do you see in that glass?

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:09.502
AUDIENCE: It's a bird.

00:14:09.502 --> 00:14:11.210
LAURIE WALLMARK: Just
a regular old bird?

00:14:14.012 --> 00:14:15.413
AUDIENCE: It's a fish bird!

00:14:15.413 --> 00:14:18.220
A flying fish.

00:14:18.220 --> 00:14:21.900
LAURIE WALLMARK: I think it is
a mechanical bird just like she

00:14:21.900 --> 00:14:23.780
was dreaming of before.

00:14:23.780 --> 00:14:27.430
Now she's seeing a machine,
this mechanical doll.

00:14:27.430 --> 00:14:29.574
And in her mind-- yeah.

00:14:29.574 --> 00:14:32.024
AUDIENCE: Why would
he make it and then--

00:14:32.024 --> 00:14:34.190
LAURIE WALLMARK: He didn't
make the mechanical doll.

