00:14:53.250 --> 00:14:55.350
"Babbage showed Ada
his difference engine,

00:14:55.350 --> 00:14:58.060
a revolutionary
mechanical calculator.

00:14:58.060 --> 00:15:01.340
He knew Ada would understand
how his extraordinary invention

00:15:01.340 --> 00:15:02.490
worked.

00:15:02.490 --> 00:15:04.460
Ada did more than understand.

00:15:04.460 --> 00:15:07.490
She couldn't wait to see the
difference engine in action.

00:15:07.490 --> 00:15:10.560
She chose to have the machine
solve a simple problem, one

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:16.030
she could easily do in
her head-- 15 times 12."

00:15:16.030 --> 00:15:18.658
OK, so how big is a calculator?

00:15:18.658 --> 00:15:20.490
AUDIENCE: Small.

00:15:20.490 --> 00:15:22.156
LAURIE WALLMARK: How
big's a calculator?

00:15:22.156 --> 00:15:22.822
AUDIENCE: Small.

00:15:22.822 --> 00:15:24.010
Enough to fit in your hand.

00:15:24.010 --> 00:15:24.968
LAURIE WALLMARK: Right.

00:15:24.968 --> 00:15:26.800
It's about hand size.

00:15:26.800 --> 00:15:29.220
It is certainly not this big.

00:15:29.220 --> 00:15:30.220
AUDIENCE: Yeah, it's a--

00:15:30.220 --> 00:15:31.553
LAURIE WALLMARK: But back then--

00:15:31.553 --> 00:15:33.224
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:15:33.224 --> 00:15:34.640
LAURIE WALLMARK:
Back then, that's

00:15:34.640 --> 00:15:37.330
what you needed to have just
something that could add,

00:15:37.330 --> 00:15:41.330
subtract, multiply, and divide.

00:15:41.330 --> 00:15:44.520
"Reaching inside the machine,
Ada rotated the metal columns

00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:47.050
until the numbers
15 and 12 appeared.

00:15:47.050 --> 00:15:50.370
With a crank of the handle,
she powered the calculator.

00:15:50.370 --> 00:15:53.930
Gears clicked and turned,
cylinders pumped up and down,

00:15:53.930 --> 00:15:57.140
small hammers clanked as
the number spiraled upward,

00:15:57.140 --> 00:15:59.960
guiding the machine to
the correct solution.

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:02.150
After a few turns of
the handle, the answer

00:16:02.150 --> 00:16:05.820
appeared on the
final column-- 180.

00:16:05.820 --> 00:16:08.110
It was right."

00:16:08.110 --> 00:16:10.020
Now, when I was doing
research for the book--

00:16:10.020 --> 00:16:12.820
and I did a lot of research,
as you can imagine--

00:16:12.820 --> 00:16:16.300
one of the things I
found was the Computer

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:21.790
Museum out in California had
built a difference engine.

00:16:21.790 --> 00:16:23.390
And they have,
speaking of YouTube,

00:16:23.390 --> 00:16:25.010
they have it on YouTube.

00:16:25.010 --> 00:16:26.900
You can see it in action.

00:16:26.900 --> 00:16:30.930
So that's how I knew about
things spiraling upward

00:16:30.930 --> 00:16:35.240
and things clanking, because I
could see the machine that they

00:16:35.240 --> 00:16:39.450
built.

00:16:39.450 --> 00:16:42.370
"Babbage told Ada he had
designed an even more powerful

00:16:42.370 --> 00:16:44.720
device, a mechanical computer.

00:16:44.720 --> 00:16:47.270
His analytical engine
would solve harder problems

00:16:47.270 --> 00:16:49.850
by working through
them step by step.

00:16:49.850 --> 00:16:53.700
It could even make decisions
all by itself, a true thinking

00:16:53.700 --> 00:16:55.470
machine.

00:16:55.470 --> 00:17:00.550
The only trouble was Babbage
hadn't actually built it.

00:17:00.550 --> 00:17:02.280
In fact, he never built it.

00:17:02.280 --> 00:17:03.360
He ran out of money.

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:09.986
Ada carried home a stack
of Babbage's lab books,

00:17:09.986 --> 00:17:13.455
30 in all, filled with notes
about the analytical engine.

00:17:13.455 --> 00:17:16.750
[INAUDIBLE] she studied
the technical descriptions

00:17:16.750 --> 00:17:19.170
and pored over the diagrams.

00:17:19.170 --> 00:17:21.880
Ada quickly realized that
without instructions,

00:17:21.880 --> 00:17:26.450
the analytical engine would be
a useless pile of metal parts.

00:17:26.450 --> 00:17:28.850
It needed numbers
to make it work--

00:17:28.850 --> 00:17:32.020
her numbers, her friends.

00:17:32.020 --> 00:17:34.180
Ada decided to
create an algorithm,

00:17:34.180 --> 00:17:35.990
a set of mathematical
instructions

00:17:35.990 --> 00:17:37.990
for the analytical engine.

00:17:37.990 --> 00:17:40.080
The machine could follow
these instructions

00:17:40.080 --> 00:17:43.150
and solve a complex math
problem, one difficult

00:17:43.150 --> 00:17:46.650
to figure out by hand."

