00:19:03.750 --> 00:19:06.490
"She worked for months,
revising her instructions.

00:19:06.490 --> 00:19:08.540
Countless lines of
numbers and symbols

00:19:08.540 --> 00:19:10.740
poured onto her journal pages.

00:19:10.740 --> 00:19:12.880
After checking and
rechecking her algorithm

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:16.560
through the night, Ada
finally laid down her pen.

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:18.920
She hadn't found any errors.

00:19:18.920 --> 00:19:22.940
The world's first computer
program was complete.

00:19:22.940 --> 00:19:25.550
The gears of Ada's mind
whirred with possibilities

00:19:25.550 --> 00:19:27.870
for future inventions,
all controlled

00:19:27.870 --> 00:19:29.970
by computing machines.

00:19:29.970 --> 00:19:31.770
She imagined computers
would someday

00:19:31.770 --> 00:19:35.780
design powerful flying machines
and majestic sailing ships.

00:19:35.780 --> 00:19:38.490
They would draw pictures
and compose music.

00:19:38.490 --> 00:19:42.530
And they would play games
and help with homework."

00:19:42.530 --> 00:19:45.330
These are things that you're
used to computers doing today,

00:19:45.330 --> 00:19:46.910
right?

00:19:46.910 --> 00:19:50.890
But back then, it truly
was revolutionary.

00:19:50.890 --> 00:19:54.980
It was like science fiction
that someone would think this.

00:19:54.980 --> 00:19:56.990
Yeah.

00:19:56.990 --> 00:19:59.914
AUDIENCE: Why would she--
wait, did you just write that?

00:19:59.914 --> 00:20:02.550
Because that's what
I'm thinking right now.

00:20:02.550 --> 00:20:05.184
LAURIE WALLMARK:
She thought that up.

00:20:05.184 --> 00:20:07.345
AUDIENCE: No, you
made the lady up.

00:20:07.345 --> 00:20:08.970
LAURIE WALLMARK: I
made the writing up,

00:20:08.970 --> 00:20:11.670
yes, but she is the one
who thought that computers

00:20:11.670 --> 00:20:13.820
might be able to compose music.

00:20:13.820 --> 00:20:16.070
She is the one that thought
that they could be used

00:20:16.070 --> 00:20:18.482
by engineers to design things.

00:20:18.482 --> 00:20:21.870
AUDIENCE: You are, because
you made her think that.

00:20:21.870 --> 00:20:25.100
LAURIE WALLMARK: Well, since she
was born in 1815, which was--

00:20:25.100 --> 00:20:26.486
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
but you made her.

00:20:26.486 --> 00:20:28.111
LAURIE WALLMARK:
[LAUGHS] In some ways,

00:20:28.111 --> 00:20:29.680
I made her come to life, yes.

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:34.060
But the other thing I want to
point out on this page, here

00:20:34.060 --> 00:20:37.270
are her notes where she
wrote the computer program.

00:20:37.270 --> 00:20:39.520
And it just says AAL.

00:20:39.520 --> 00:20:44.060
It stands for either Ada
Augusta Lovelace or Augusta Ada

00:20:44.060 --> 00:20:44.770
Lovelace.

00:20:44.770 --> 00:20:46.390
And I can never
remember which one,

00:20:46.390 --> 00:20:48.410
and I always forget
to keep looking it up.

00:20:48.410 --> 00:20:53.090
But the important part is
it's only her initials.

00:20:53.090 --> 00:20:56.160
Why didn't she sign her name
to this very important work

00:20:56.160 --> 00:20:57.914
that she did?

00:20:57.914 --> 00:21:00.152
AUDIENCE: Because she
didn't want to brag.

00:21:00.152 --> 00:21:01.860
LAURIE WALLMARK: She
didn't want to brag.

00:21:01.860 --> 00:21:02.720
That could be.

00:21:02.720 --> 00:21:03.470
What do you think?

00:21:03.470 --> 00:21:04.478
Why do you think?

00:21:04.478 --> 00:21:07.522
AUDIENCE: Because
she didn't want to.

00:21:07.522 --> 00:21:09.520
You made her do that.

00:21:09.520 --> 00:21:10.394
Because you made her.

00:21:10.394 --> 00:21:11.393
LAURIE WALLMARK: Uh-huh.

00:21:11.393 --> 00:21:12.926
Dads, why do you think?

00:21:12.926 --> 00:21:15.210
AUDIENCE: Maybe she didn't
want the [INAUDIBLE].

00:21:15.210 --> 00:21:17.500
LAURIE WALLMARK: They
didn't want-- she was afraid

00:21:17.500 --> 00:21:20.210
if people knew she
was a woman, they

00:21:20.210 --> 00:21:22.390
wouldn't take it seriously.

00:21:22.390 --> 00:21:26.500
They would think, oh, it's just
a girl, a woman who did that,

00:21:26.500 --> 00:21:28.570
so it can't be right.

00:21:28.570 --> 00:21:29.400
But it was right.

00:21:29.400 --> 00:21:34.330
It was revolutionary back
in that time and even later.

